(     4.  These are:  \(1\) The Moral Law; \(2\) Heaven;  \(3\)  Earth;\015)'
(\(4\) The Commander; \(5\) Method and discipline.\015)'
(\015)'
(     [It appears from what follows that Sun Tzu means by  "Moral\015)'
(Law" a principle of harmony, not unlike the Tao of Lao Tzu in its\015)'
(moral aspect.  One might be tempted to render it by  "morale,"\015)'
(were it not considered as an attribute of the ruler in ss. 13.]\015)'
(\015)'
(     5,  6.  The MORAL LAW causes the people to be in complete\015)'
(accord with their ruler, so that they will follow him regardless\015)'
(of their lives, undismayed by any danger.\015)'
(\015)'
(     [Tu Yu quotes Wang Tzu as saying:   "Without constant\015)'
(practice,  the officers will be nervous and undecided when\015)'
(mustering for battle; without constant practice, the general will\015)'
(be wavering and irresolute when the crisis is at hand."]\015)'
(\015)'
(     7.  HEAVEN signifies night and day, cold and heat, times and\015)'
(seasons.\015)'
(\015)'
(     [The commentators, I think, make an unnecessary mystery of\015)'
(two words here.  Meng Shih refers to "the hard and the soft,\015)'
(waxing and waning" of Heaven.  Wang Hsi, however, may be right in\015)'
(saying that what is meant is "the general economy of Heaven,"\015)'
(including the five elements, the four seasons, wind and clouds,\015)'
(and other phenomena.]\015)'
(\015)'
(     8.  EARTH comprises distances, great and small; danger and\015)'
(security; open ground and narrow passes; the chances of life and\015)'
(death.\015)'
(     9.  The COMMANDER stands for the virtues of   wisdom,\015)'
(sincerely, benevolence, courage and strictness.\015)'
(\015)'
(     [The five cardinal virtues of the Chinese are \(1\)  humanity\015)'
(or benevolence; \(2\) uprightness of mind; \(3\) self-respect,  self-\015)'
(control,  or "proper feeling;" \(4\) wisdom; \(5\) sincerity or good\015)'
(faith.  Here "wisdom" and "sincerity" are put before "humanity or\015)'
(benevolence,"  and the two military virtues of  "courage"  and\015)'
("strictness"  substituted for "uprightness of mind"  and  "self-\015)'
(respect, self-control, or 'proper feeling.'"]\015)'
(\015)'
(     10.  By METHOD AND DISCIPLINE are to be understood the\015)'
(marshaling   of the army in its proper   subdivisions,   the\015)'
(graduations of rank among the officers, the maintenance of roads\015)'
(by which supplies may reach the army, and the control of military\015)'
(expenditure.\015)'
(     11.  These five heads should be familiar to every general:\015)'
(he who knows them will be victorious; he who knows them not will\015)'
(fail.\015)'
